{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17639224","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17639224"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T19:04:18+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T19:04:18+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17764"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17764","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17764"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.03,0.1,0,0.76]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10478"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72738"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"10478","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/10478"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17764"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58208"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"25"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"247"},{"type":"tags","id":"1478"},{"type":"tags","id":"2968"},{"type":"tags","id":"4935"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"7017"},{"type":"tags","id":"8088"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"24454"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24457"},{"type":"contributions","id":"24526"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72738","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/72738"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 35-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic with a one-day history of a painful lump in her left breast. She recently had a child and has been mostly breastfeeding normally. She has temporarily stopped breastfeeding due to the pain. She reports that the lump is only on her left breast and has noticed some cracks in the nipple. She also feels generally unwell, with a fever and chills.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Breast abscess","Breast engorgement","Blocked milk duct","Fibroadenoma","Lactational mastitis"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient presents with symptoms suggestive of \u003Cstrong\u003Elactational mastitis\u003C/strong\u003E, a common condition in breastfeeding women. It is characterised by breast pain, swelling, and erythema, often associated with cracked nipples, which can allow bacteria to enter and cause infection. The sudden onset of pain and the presence of a lump are typical features. Patients often have a fever and flu-like symptoms.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Ebreast abscess\u003C/strong\u003E may develop if mastitis is not treated promptly, but it typically presents with more severe symptoms and systemic signs of infection, such as fever.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Eblocked milk duct\u003C/strong\u003E can also cause a painful lump, but it is usually not associated with cracked nipples or signs of infection. It often resolves with continued breastfeeding or milk expression.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EBreast engorgement\u003C/strong\u003E occurs when the breasts are overly full of milk, leading to swelling and discomfort. It is usually bilateral and not associated with cracked nipples or infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EA \u003Cstrong\u003Efibroadenoma\u003C/strong\u003E is a benign breast tumour that typically presents as a painless, mobile lump and is not related to breastfeeding or infection.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Lactational mastitis is a common condition in breastfeeding women, often presenting with breast pain, swelling, and erythema.","Prompt treatment with antibiotics and continued breastfeeding or milk expression is recommended to prevent complications such as abscess formation.","Cracked nipples can be a risk factor for developing mastitis due to bacterial entry."],"references":["Pevzner M, Dahan A. Mastitis While Breastfeeding: Prevention, the Importance of Proper Treatment, and Potential Complications. J Clin Med. 2020 Jul 22;9(8):2328. doi: 10.3390/jcm9082328. PMID: 32707832; PMCID: PMC7465810.","Wilson E, Woodd SL, Benova L. Incidence of and Risk Factors for Lactational Mastitis: A Systematic Review. J Hum Lact. 2020 Nov;36(4):673-686. doi: 10.1177/0890334420907898. Epub 2020 Apr 14. PMID: 32286139; PMCID: PMC7672676.","Morcomb EF, Dargel CM, Anderson SA. Mastitis: Rapid Evidence Review. Am Fam Physician. 2024 Aug;110(2):174-182. PMID: 39172675.","Wilson E, Woodd SL, Benova L. Incidence of and Risk Factors for Lactational Mastitis: A Systematic Review. J Hum Lact. 2020 Nov;36(4):673-686. doi: 10.1177/0890334420907898. Epub 2020 Apr 14. PMID: 32286139; PMCID: PMC7672676."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58208"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17764"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"58208","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/58208"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-22T07:42:06+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-22T07:42:39+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"10478"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"72738"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"25","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/25"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udc68\u200d\ud83d\udc69\u200d\ud83d\udc66","name":"General Practice","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"6